{{About|bridges in musical composition|the component of a musical instrument|Bridge (instrument)|the benefit concerts organized by Neil Young and his wife|Bridge School Benefit|the bridge in the thirty-two-bar form|Thirty-two-bar form#Middle eight}}
[[Image:Jazz standard bridge.png|thumb|right|350px|The [[ragtime progression]] (E7-A7-D7-G7) often appears in the bridge of [[jazz standard]]s ({{audio|Jazz standard bridge.mid|Play}}).<ref>Boyd, Bill (1997). ''Jazz Chord Progressions'', p.56. {{ISBN|0-7935-7038-7}}.</ref> The III7-VI7-II7-V7 (or V7/V/V/V - V7/V/V - V7/V - V7) [[circle progression]] leads back to C major (I) but is itself indefinite in key.]] In [[music]], especially western [[popular music]], a '''bridge''' is a contrasting [[section (music)|section]] that prepares for the return of the original material section. In a piece in which the original material or melody is referred to as the "A" section, the bridge may be the third eight-[[bar (music)|bar]] [[phrase (music)|phrase]] in a [[thirty-two-bar form]] (the B in AABA), or may be used more loosely in [[verse-chorus form]], or, in a [[compound AABA form]], used as a contrast to a full AABA section.
The term comes from a German word for bridge, ''Steg'', used by the [[Meistersinger]]s of the 15th to the 18th century to describe a [[transition (music)|transitional]] section in medieval [[bar form]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Horst|first=Brunner|title=Bar Form|journal=New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|year=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford}}</ref> The German term became widely known in 1920s Germany through musicologist [[Alfred Lorenz]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Lorenz|first=Alfred|title=Das Geheimnis der Form bei Richard Wagner|year=1924|location=Berlin}}</ref> and his exhaustive studies of [[Richard Wagner]]'s adaptations of bar form in his popular 19th-century neo-medieval operas. The term entered the English lexicon in the 1930s—translated as ''bridge''—via composers fleeing Nazi Germany who, working in Hollywood and on Broadway, used the term to describe similar transitional sections in the American popular music they were writing.
== Role == {{expand section|elaborations on the difference between a bridge and a pre-chorus. Are there contemporary examples contrasting the two?|date=March 2011}}
The bridge is often used to contrast with and prepare for the return of the [[Song structure (popular music)#Verse|verse]] and the [[refrain|chorus]]. "The b section of the popular song chorus is often called the ''bridge'' or ''release''."<ref>Benward & Saker (2003). ''Music: In Theory and Practice'', Vol. I, p.318. Seventh Edition. {{ISBN|978-0-07-294262-0}}. Emphasis original.</ref> For example, the B of AABA in thirty-two-bar form, with the verse surrounding the whole. While the bridge in verse-chorus and other forms is C, for example: ABABCAB. Lyrically, the bridge is typically used to pause and reflect on the earlier portions of the song or to prepare the listener for the climax. The term may also refer to the section between the verse and the chorus, though this is more commonly called the ''[[pre-Chorus|pre-chorus]]'' or ''link''. The lyrics of the theme, "[[The Song That Goes Like This]]", from the musical play ''[[Spamalot]]'' spoofs the abuse of the bridge in romantic songwriting: "Now we can go straight / into the middle eight / a bridge that is too far for me".{{citation needed|date=January 2012}} Similarly, in the ''[[Axis of Awesome]]'' song "This Is How You Write a Love Song", the lyrics humorously map the movement of the song from chorus to chorus using bridges.{{citation needed|date=January 2012}} In the song "[[Get Up (I Feel Like Being a) Sex Machine]]", [[James Brown]] asks if he can "take the band to the bridge". [[Led Zeppelin]] makes an [[in-joke]] regarding the use of bridges in popular music in their song "[[The Crunge]]", asking, at the end, "Where's the confounded bridge?" The song, humorously, does not have a bridge.{{citation needed|date=January 2012}}
== Classical music == [[File:MusikSequenz.png|thumbnail|right|400px|A bridge in J.S. Bach's Fugue in G major BWV 860, mm. 17-19.{{audio|MusikSequenz.mid|Play}}]]
Bridges are also common in [[European classical music|classical music]], and are known as a specific [[Sequence (music)|Sequence]] form—also known as transitions. Formally called a '''bridge-passage''', they delineate separate sections of an extended work, or smooth what would otherwise be an abrupt modulation, such as the transition between the two [[Theme (music)|themes]] of a [[sonata form]]. In the latter context, this transition between two musical [[Subject (music)|subjects]] is often referred to as the "transition theme";<ref>[http://www.songstuff.com/glossary/ Songstuff Music Glossary]</ref> indeed, in later [[Romantic music|Romantic]] symphonies such as [[Antonín Dvořák|Dvořák]]'s [[Symphony No. 9 (Dvořák)|New World Symphony]] or [[César Franck]]'s [[Symphony in D minor (Franck)|Symphony in D minor]], the transition theme becomes almost a third subject in itself.<ref>Collins Music Encyclopedia, London 1959, article "Symphony"</ref>
The latter work also provides several good examples of a short bridge to smooth a [[Modulation (music)|modulation]]. Instead of simply repeating the whole [[sonata form#Exposition|exposition]] in the original key, as would be done in a symphony of the [[Classical period (music)|classical period]], Franck repeats the first subject a minor third higher in F minor. A two-bar bridge achieves this transition with Frank's characteristic combination of [[Modulation (music)#Enharmonic modulation|enharmonic]] and [[Modulation (music)#Chromatic modulation|chromatic modulation]]. After the repeat of the first subject, another bridge of four bars leads into the transition theme in F major, the key of the true second subject.
In a [[fugue]], a bridge is, "...a short passage at the end of the first entrance of the answer and the beginning of the second entrance of the subject. Its purpose is to modulate back to the tonic key (subject) from the answer (which is in the dominant key). Not all fugues include a bridge."<ref>Benward & Saker (2009). ''Music in Theory and Practice: Volume II'', p.51. Eighth Edition. {{ISBN|978-0-07-310188-0}}.</ref>
An example of a bridge-passage that separates two sections of a more loosely organized work occurs in [[George Gershwin]]'s ''[[An American in Paris]]''. As [[Deems Taylor]] described it in the program notes for the first performance: "Having safely eluded the taxis ... the American's itinerary becomes somewhat obscured. ... However, since what immediately ensues is technically known as a bridge-passage, one is reasonably justified in assuming that the Gershwin pen ... has perpetrated a musical pun and that ... our American has crossed the Seine, and is somewhere on the Left Bank."<ref>[[An American in Paris]] & "''george gershwin's an american in paris piano solo''" [sic], Warner Bros. Publications Inc., 1929 (renewed), p. 36</ref>
