{{Infobox language |name=Savosavo |states=[[Solomon Islands]] |region=Savo Island, north of Guadalcanal, Central Solomons. |speakers={{sigfig|2415|2}} |date=1999 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Central Solomons languages|Central Solomons]] |iso3=svs |glotto=savo1255 |glottorefname=Savosavo }}
The '''Savosavo''' language is an endangered language spoken on [[Savo Island|Savo]], a small volcanic island north of [[Guadalcanal]] in the [[Solomon Islands]]. Savosavo is one of the [[Central Solomons languages|Central Solomon languages]] which are part of the [[East Papuan languages|Papuan]] language family, unlike most of the languages in the vicinity, which are members of the [[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] branch of the [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]] language family. The nearest Papuan language to Savosavo is [[Lavukaleve language|Lavukaleve]].
== Phonology == Savosavo has five vowels and 17 consonants<ref>Wegener, Claudia. 2012. A grammar of Savosavo. Berlin: de Gruyter.</ref>.
{| class="wikitable" |+Vowels ! !Front !Back |- !Close |i |u |- !Close-mid |e |o |- !Open |a | |} {| class="wikitable" |+Consonants ! colspan="2" | ![[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] |- ! rowspan="2" |[[Stop consonant|Stop]] !{{Small|voiceless}} |[[Voiceless bilabial stop|p]] |[[Voiceless dental and alveolar stops|t]] | |[[Voiceless velar stop|k]] |- !{{Small|[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} |[[Voiced bilabial stop|b]] |[[Voiced dental and alveolar stops|d]] |[[Voiced palatal stop|ɟ]] |[[Voiced velar stop|g]] |- ! rowspan="2" |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] !{{Small|voiceless}} | |[[Voiceless alveolar fricative|s]] | | |- !{{Small|[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} |[[Voiced bilabial fricative|β]] |[[Voiced alveolar fricative|z]] | | |- ! colspan="2" |[[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |[[Bilabial nasal|m]] |[[Dental, alveolar and postalveolar nasals|n]] |[[Palatal nasal|ɲ]] |[[Velar nasal|ŋ]] |- ! colspan="2" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | |[[Dental, alveolar and postalveolar lateral approximants|l]] | |[[Voiced velar approximant|ɰ]] |- ! colspan="2" |[[Trill consonant|Trill]] | |[[Dental, alveolar and postalveolar trills|r]] | | |} Vowels have no length contrast, and the vowels /e/, /i/, /o/, and /u/ vary freely between different allophones.
== Orthography == The Savosavo language has 5 vowels (a, e, i, o, u) and 17 consonants (b, d, g, gh, j, k, l, m, n, gn, ng, p, r, s, t, v, z). This is the Anglican orthography. In the Catholic orthography G is written Q and Gh is written G. In other orthographies Gn is written Ñ and Ng is written N̄.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omniglot.com/writing/savosavo.htm|title=Savosavo language, alphabet and pronunciation|website=www.omniglot.com|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref>
